@realmoney Mr. Market Continues to Show Signs of a Top and a Breakdown Away from my frenetic (and hopefully opportunistic trading), I want to reiterate what I wrote earlier today and leave you with this thought as we approach the end of the trading day and the beginning of t

the weekend: As the business media dwells on the (UBER) IPO, the market backdrop continues to deteriorate. I continue to see growing evidence that the market could be in a major topping process - with prior highs (and a possible "triple top") reached at January 2018,

September 2018 and early May 2019. I see consequential breakdowns in a wide swatch of stocks (e.g., Apple (AAPL) , Home Depot (HD) , Caterpillar (CAT) , Boeing (BA) , 3M (MMM) , etc.) Most traders and investors are ill advised to short.
For those that are less aggressive and risk averse, I suggest that the front end of the curve (two years or less) represents an excellent risk free rate of return relative to equities and inflation.
Pieces of paper yielding 2.3%-2.45% seems fine to me given the economic, political and market uncertainties.
Thanks for watching my Twitter thread this week. Enjoy the weekend, all.

From my opener on @realmoney this morning: I remain negative on any long term agreement with the U.S. and China. From my perch, the whole negotiation has been a farce - dominated by an Administration who prefers "a beautiful" letters and personal appearances above lengthy

and complicated negotiations. China will never become a good actor as obstacles from IP theft/technology to human rights represent insurmountable headwinds. And, as discussed often, the timeframes of the U.S. and China are far different. So, rather than focusing on much

more trade-related downside to the markets - we should consider that the failed negotiations will likely dampen and put a cap to the market's short- to intermediate- term upside potential. @jimcramer @tomkeene @SquawkCNBC @cnbcfastmoney @TeamCavuto @lizclaman @michaelsantoli

On @realmoney Cautious Market Positioning and "Second Level Thinking" Explains the Modest Market Impact (on Futures) of the Imposition of Tariffs on China To me, the trade deal with China "smelled" from the beginning.

However, for now, I feel the market and economic impact of a negative trade outcome between U.S. and China has been materially discounted for these reasons: 1. Market positioning has grown much more cautious. (See Divine's tweet on the rising put/call ratio)

2. Its another example of "first level thinking" v. "second level thinking." "First level thinking" is that the tariffs will be put on and that is negative for the markets. "Second level thinking" is that the tariffs will be put on but, over the short term,

the market has discounted much of the impact 3. The most likely outcome is that no fundamental progress will be made between the big issues. But worries of a sharp escalation seems unlikely, too, as neither country can afford it. @jimcramer @tomkeene @SquawkCNBC @CNBCFastMoney
